p:
The roots of 
 Eriosema chinense Vogel (syn. 
 Eriosema himalaicum H. Ohashi; 
 Eriosema tuberosum (Ham.) Wang et Tang) are reported to be used as food in Northern Australia, China and North East India and against diarrhea in Meghalaya (India) (
 Neogi et al., 1989; 
 Martin and Ryan, 2004; 
 Prasad et al., 2013a). In Yunnan Province of China, the roots are used against diarrhea, orchitis, hydrophobia and as detoxifying medicine (
 Kunming Institute of Botany, 1979). In Thailand, the fresh roots are eaten as a tonic, and decoctions of the seeds are used for wound healing and for their diuretic properties (
 Thongnest et al., 2013). Such decoctions are also well-known as astringent, diuretic, tonic, against cold sweats and during delivery to promote discharge of the lochia. Decoctions additionally containing powdered pepper are given for diarrhea (
 Ashraf and Borthakur, 2005; 
 Laloo and Hemalatha, 2011; 
 Prasad et al., 2013c; 
 Thongnest et al., 2013).
